1
00:00:16,716 --> 00:00:19,514
Kate Reddy?
I've known her six years.

2
00:00:19,652 --> 00:00:21,313
Smartest girl I know.

3
00:00:21,454 --> 00:00:23,388
And a heart of gold, too.

4
00:00:23,523 --> 00:00:26,458
All us working mothers feel
like we're spinning 50 plates

5
00:00:26,593 --> 00:00:29,084
in they air at once, but Kate,
you can give her ten more plates,

6
00:00:29,229 --> 00:00:31,390
all the size of manhole covers,
and she just keeps going.

7
00:00:31,531 --> 00:00:34,125
Big report due the
next day at work, done.

8
00:00:34,267 --> 00:00:37,259
Sew some extra fairy wings
on for Emily's recital, she's doing it.

9
00:00:37,404 --> 00:00:41,431
Last minute in-laws show up, she can
do it without mixing vodka and Xanax.

10
00:00:41,574 --> 00:00:43,804
It's amazing.
I'm telling you, she's amazing.

11
00:00:47,947 --> 00:00:51,439
For all of us moms, there comes a time
when you almost don't pull it off,

12
00:00:51,584 --> 00:00:56,078
and, um, for Kate, that was
those three months last winter.

13
00:00:56,222 --> 00:00:59,658
And all that trouble started
with the bake sale.

14
00:01:00,760 --> 00:01:02,625
[chuckling] Did she tell you
about the bake sale?

15
00:01:03,329 --> 00:01:05,524
[Kate] Oh, my God,
the kindergarten bake sale.

16
00:01:05,665 --> 00:01:06,461
[phone beeps]

17
00:01:06,599 --> 00:01:09,124
I had just flown home to
Boston from a business trip.

18
00:01:09,269 --> 00:01:13,763
But then I got the reminder
from Emily's school about the bake sale.

19
00:01:15,542 --> 00:01:18,010
I promised Emily that I'd
make something homemade

20
00:01:18,144 --> 00:01:20,578
and I was prepared to
stay up all night to do it.

21
00:01:20,713 --> 00:01:24,274
But the deli was
out of baking supplies.

22
00:01:26,953 --> 00:01:31,219
This pie was going to be homemade
if it was the last thing I did.

23
00:01:32,892 --> 00:01:35,156
Why did I care?
Well, first of all,

24
00:01:35,295 --> 00:01:40,232
the other mothers are like a tiny army
of mini Martha Stewarts.

25
00:01:40,366 --> 00:01:42,561
Their contributions would look perfect.

26
00:01:42,702 --> 00:01:44,727
Their daughters would feel proud.

27
00:01:44,871 --> 00:01:47,601
I just wanted Em
to feel the same way.

28
00:01:47,740 --> 00:01:51,267
I'm trying to prevent the newsflash,
20 years from now.

29
00:01:51,411 --> 00:01:55,848
Friends trace the start of Emily Reddy's
mental problems to a school bake sale

30
00:01:55,982 --> 00:01:58,849
where her mother, a shadowy
presence in her life,

31
00:01:58,985 --> 00:02:01,453
humiliated her
in front of her classmates.

32
00:02:03,189 --> 00:02:05,851
[Kate] I was not
gonna let Emily down.

33
00:02:08,361 --> 00:02:10,795
[moaning] Spread out,
spread out, spread out...

34
00:02:10,930 --> 00:02:12,363
Bigger, bigger, bigger...

35
00:02:18,738 --> 00:02:21,332
[Kate] You don't understand.
I still remember the looks I got

36
00:02:21,474 --> 00:02:25,501
in 1974, when my mother
sent me to the school bake sale

37
00:02:25,645 --> 00:02:28,307
with two cans
of sliced peaches.

38
00:02:39,592 --> 00:02:41,253
You made a pie.

39
00:02:41,394 --> 00:02:43,862
- Hi!
- Hi, welcome home.

40
00:02:43,997 --> 00:02:48,058
Thanks. I... I thought maybe
the powdered sugar would help.

41
00:02:48,201 --> 00:02:50,863
[chuckles] No. No,
we're way past help on this.

42
00:02:51,004 --> 00:02:54,599
Come to bed. Listen,
we got Chips Ahoy here.

43
00:02:54,741 --> 00:02:56,402
We can throw these in her backpack.
She'll be good to go.

44
00:02:56,543 --> 00:02:57,737
Are you kidding me?

45
00:02:57,877 --> 00:03:00,539
Do you have any idea what those
dietetically correct mothers

46
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:04,309
would do if I brought cookies with
high fructose corn syrup and salt?

47
00:03:04,450 --> 00:03:06,850
Oh, my God, that sounds really good.
Can I have like a little...?

48
00:03:06,986 --> 00:03:08,476
Mm...

49
00:03:09,255 --> 00:03:11,849
- Mm! Yeah.
- Hm? See?

50
00:03:11,991 --> 00:03:15,620
- You worry too much.
- Well, you know, I just...

51
00:03:15,762 --> 00:03:18,356
I just want Emily to feel proud
of what she brings to the bake sale.

52
00:03:18,498 --> 00:03:20,557
I don't want her to feel different
from the other kids because her mother

53
00:03:20,700 --> 00:03:22,930
has to travel for work, you know?
I just...

54
00:03:23,069 --> 00:03:26,869
- I want her to know I tried.
- All right, I take it back.

55
00:03:27,006 --> 00:03:28,997
Those are nice things
to want for her.

56
00:03:30,577 --> 00:03:33,603
- [man] Hey, how was Phoenix?
- Oh, it was fine.

57
00:03:33,746 --> 00:03:37,341
You know, airport, taxi, meeting,

58
00:03:37,483 --> 00:03:41,044
hotel, meeting, taxi, airport.

59
00:03:42,188 --> 00:03:45,351
You must, be, uh... exhausted.

60
00:03:45,491 --> 00:03:49,860
Oh! Well... a little.

61
00:03:53,399 --> 00:03:54,627
But not completely.

62
00:03:54,767 --> 00:03:56,098
[# Betty Everett: "Shoop Shoop"]

63
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:58,101
# Does he love me?
I wanna know

64
00:03:58,238 --> 00:03:59,830
[Kate] I'm not one
of those wives who doesn't

65
00:03:59,973 --> 00:04:01,600
wanna have sex
with her husband.

66
00:04:01,741 --> 00:04:04,141
I still think he's
the cutest guy I know.

67
00:04:04,277 --> 00:04:08,577
His adorable little frown lines,
his seaweed-colored eyes,

68
00:04:08,715 --> 00:04:11,775
the way he smells after a shower.

69
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:14,079
There 's just one problem.

70
00:04:14,220 --> 00:04:15,380
# It's in his kiss # #

71
00:04:15,521 --> 00:04:21,153
- [music stops]
- [snoring]

72
00:04:53,926 --> 00:04:55,917
[laughs]

73
00:05:12,612 --> 00:05:16,548
[Kate] A recent study showed that
64 percent of women with young children

74
00:05:16,683 --> 00:05:18,651
don't sleep through the night.

75
00:05:18,785 --> 00:05:21,913
Researchers were at a loss
to explain why.

76
00:05:22,055 --> 00:05:23,215
They could have asked me.

77
00:05:23,923 --> 00:05:27,984
At night, I, like women
all around the world, do the list:

78
00:05:28,428 --> 00:05:31,625
Emily's birthday party theme.
Pirates or pop stars?

79
00:05:31,764 --> 00:05:34,198
Things to buy: paper towels,
toothpaste, pork chops.

80
00:05:34,334 --> 00:05:36,199
Buy a present
for Jedda 's birthday party.

81
00:05:36,336 --> 00:05:38,327
Find out Jedda: boy or girl?

82
00:05:38,471 --> 00:05:39,961
Call the guy about the thing.
Make a playdate for Emily

83
00:05:40,106 --> 00:05:41,505
with that kid that doesn't bite.

84
00:05:41,641 --> 00:05:43,165
Refill washer fluid in car.
Wait a minute.

85
00:05:43,309 --> 00:05:44,640
Shouldn't that be
on Richard's list?

86
00:05:44,777 --> 00:05:46,745
Who am I kidding?
Richard doesn't have a list.

87
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:48,744
Wax something, anything.

88
00:05:48,881 --> 00:05:50,815
- [hair ripping]
- Call Richard's mother and say hi.

89
00:05:50,950 --> 00:05:52,747
- [phone rings]
- Or just email hi.

90
00:05:52,885 --> 00:05:54,182
- [computer dings]
- Wash Ben's teddy bear.

91
00:05:54,320 --> 00:05:56,015
Renew birth control pills.
Twinkies...

92
00:05:56,155 --> 00:05:57,782
...Ambien while I'm at it.
Finish year-end fiscal summary.

93
00:05:57,924 --> 00:06:00,051
Hamster. Oh, no,
start year-end fiscal summary.

94
00:06:00,193 --> 00:06:02,923
...new ways to say no.
Kegels? [gasps]

95
00:06:03,062 --> 00:06:04,051
Bagels!

96
00:06:10,870 --> 00:06:13,703
[laughs, screeches]

97
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:15,671
[Kate] When I come home
after a trip,

98
00:06:15,808 --> 00:06:17,742
Ben doesn't hold
my absence against me.

99
00:06:17,877 --> 00:06:20,004
- Hey, baby.
- He's too little for grudges.

100
00:06:20,146 --> 00:06:22,808
- Little buddy, hi! Boo!
- Boo! [laughs]

101
00:06:24,217 --> 00:06:26,447
[Kate] I love being a mother of
a two-year-old boy.

102
00:06:26,586 --> 00:06:28,144
It's like being a movie star

103
00:06:28,287 --> 00:06:30,118
- in a world without critics.
- Hi, Em.

104
00:06:30,256 --> 00:06:33,987
[Kate] Unfortunately, my daughter
isn't quite as forgiving.

105
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:36,322
If I'm gone for too long,
she rewards me

106
00:06:36,462 --> 00:06:38,726
with a game of snubs and punishments.

107
00:06:38,865 --> 00:06:41,026
- I want Daddy to take me to school.
- [buzzer sounds]

108
00:06:41,167 --> 00:06:42,691
- Paula gives me a bath.
- [buzzer sounds]

109
00:06:42,835 --> 00:06:45,929
- I don't like hugs.
- [buzzer sounds]

110
00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:47,733
[crowd] Aw!

111
00:06:51,711 --> 00:06:54,544
Any working mother who says
she doesn't bribe her kids

112
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:56,739
can add "liar" to her resume.

113
00:06:57,650 --> 00:07:00,141
Who wants to watch cartoons?!

114
00:07:00,286 --> 00:07:04,416
[shouting] I got your
happy ending right here!

115
00:07:04,557 --> 00:07:07,651
- [gasping] You swine!
- [laughing]

116
00:07:07,794 --> 00:07:10,422
- [TV continues, indistinct]
- Good morning.

117
00:07:10,563 --> 00:07:13,361
Hey, we gotta call Beachwood Carpets
and get an estimate on those stairs.

118
00:07:13,499 --> 00:07:16,024
Oh, you say the nicest things.

119
00:07:16,169 --> 00:07:18,194
Something's different about you.
You're...

120
00:07:18,337 --> 00:07:19,929
Not in a shirt with barf on it?

121
00:07:20,072 --> 00:07:21,539
Your big meeting, it's today, right?

122
00:07:21,674 --> 00:07:23,039
I'm getting the gig. Definitely.

123
00:07:23,176 --> 00:07:25,303
Get a sitter.
Tonight, we are celebrating!

124
00:07:25,445 --> 00:07:26,503
- Done.
- I mean it.

125
00:07:26,646 --> 00:07:28,204
Who cares if I'm up against huge firms

126
00:07:28,347 --> 00:07:31,612
with portfolios filled with
museum wings and hotel lobbies?

127
00:07:31,751 --> 00:07:33,776
I have a fantastic bathroom in Back Bay

128
00:07:33,920 --> 00:07:36,889
and a mind-blowing basement
renovation in New Hampshire.

129
00:07:37,023 --> 00:07:40,083
- Not to mention a shirt without barf.
- Mm. I better get it.

130
00:07:40,226 --> 00:07:42,990
I picked the worst time to go on my own.
It's like the economy was waiting for me

131
00:07:43,129 --> 00:07:45,029
to start my own business and then tank.

132
00:07:45,164 --> 00:07:47,724
- Richard.
- No, Kate, I am bankrolling this firm

133
00:07:47,867 --> 00:07:49,300
with change from our sock drawer.

134
00:07:49,435 --> 00:07:52,199
Well, that's gonna change.
It has to, because you're too talented

135
00:07:52,338 --> 00:07:54,329
- for it not to.
- [sighs] I hope so.

136
00:07:54,474 --> 00:07:56,635
The pay isn't much,
but in the long run,

137
00:07:56,776 --> 00:07:59,074
- it'll be great for both of us.
- You're gonna get it.

138
00:07:59,212 --> 00:08:00,679
- Am I gonna get it?
- You are gonna get it.

139
00:08:00,813 --> 00:08:02,644
- I'm gonna get it! OK.
- [laughs]

140
00:08:02,782 --> 00:08:03,806
- I gotta go.
- No, no, wait, wait!

141
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:05,110
Can you just wait one second

142
00:08:05,251 --> 00:08:08,152
- while I take a really quick shower?
- Where the hell is Paula?

143
00:08:08,287 --> 00:08:10,881
She's been late every day this week.
Honestly, I'm gonna talk to her.

144
00:08:11,023 --> 00:08:12,854
Oh, no, Richard,
please don't talk to her! Please.

145
00:08:12,992 --> 00:08:14,653
If we don't keep her happy,
she'll leave.

146
00:08:15,628 --> 00:08:17,323
Would that be the worst
thing in the world?

147
00:08:17,463 --> 00:08:20,193
Uh, frankly, at this point,
it would be easier if you left.

148
00:08:21,167 --> 00:08:22,998
You know what I mean.

149
00:08:23,135 --> 00:08:24,864
- [children laughing]
- [door opens]

150
00:08:25,004 --> 00:08:26,938
- She's here! She's here.
- [Paula] Good morning.

151
00:08:27,073 --> 00:08:29,166
- [indistinct chatter]
- [Kate] Men and women

152
00:08:29,308 --> 00:08:31,572
Iook at childcare very differently.

153
00:08:31,711 --> 00:08:34,976
- The surf was beautiful today.
- [Kate] Richard sees an outflow of cash

154
00:08:35,114 --> 00:08:36,206
we badly need at the moment,

155
00:08:36,349 --> 00:08:39,375
and I see a person who knows
which blankie Ben likes.

156
00:08:43,956 --> 00:08:47,824
It's a good job. I love the kids,
and Kate is a great boss.

157
00:08:47,960 --> 00:08:50,758
What does Kate do for a living?
I have no idea.

158
00:08:50,897 --> 00:08:54,162
Works in a bank?
Is she... is she like a teller?

159
00:08:54,934 --> 00:08:56,196
[Emily] Come on, Mom,
we're gonna be late.

160
00:08:56,335 --> 00:08:58,860
Hey, Paula, can you put
this in a container for me?

161
00:08:59,005 --> 00:09:00,267
Sure.

162
00:09:00,406 --> 00:09:04,638
- You... made a pie?
- Yep.

163
00:09:05,478 --> 00:09:08,379
[school bell rings]

164
00:09:08,514 --> 00:09:12,109
[Kate] OK, can I just say that I work
for a high-powered investment firm,

165
00:09:12,251 --> 00:09:14,310
yet nothing scares me more

166
00:09:14,453 --> 00:09:17,251
than being caught by my
daughter's kindergarten teacher

167
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:19,290
when we're late for circle time.

168
00:09:19,425 --> 00:09:21,484
Does Mama love you
a little or a lot?

169
00:09:21,627 --> 00:09:22,855
- A little.
- [gasps]

170
00:09:22,995 --> 00:09:25,964
- [laughs] A lot.
- A lot! Oh!

171
00:09:26,098 --> 00:09:28,589
Have a good day, OK?
I love you. Goodbye. Go.

172
00:09:28,734 --> 00:09:31,225
Go, go, go, go, go, go. [sighs]

173
00:09:31,370 --> 00:09:33,395
[teacher] Late again,
Mrs. Reddy?

174
00:09:35,508 --> 00:09:37,066
Yeah, sorry.

175
00:09:37,209 --> 00:09:39,006
We'll do better tomorrow.

176
00:09:39,145 --> 00:09:40,442
Perhaps.

177
00:09:42,648 --> 00:09:44,980
- Good morning.
- You baked a pie, really?

178
00:09:45,117 --> 00:09:46,448
Are you trying
to make me look bad?

179
00:09:46,586 --> 00:09:49,054
It's from the deli
around the corner.

180
00:09:49,188 --> 00:09:51,850
And you distressed it? Nice!

181
00:09:51,991 --> 00:09:54,255
Did you have to throw away the
package before the nanny saw it?

182
00:09:54,393 --> 00:09:55,587
Well, duh.

183
00:09:55,728 --> 00:09:58,288
[Kate] This is my friend Allison.
Oh, wait, you've already met her, right.

184
00:09:58,431 --> 00:10:00,592
She's a single mom, and I can always

185
00:10:00,733 --> 00:10:02,860
count on Allison,
especially for things like

186
00:10:03,002 --> 00:10:06,199
making something much worse
than I did for the bake sale.

187
00:10:06,339 --> 00:10:08,466
That is unset Jell-O, folks.

188
00:10:08,608 --> 00:10:10,542
Kate and I bonded immediately.

189
00:10:10,676 --> 00:10:12,667
A working mother needs solidarity.

190
00:10:12,812 --> 00:10:15,679
And we know where we rank
in likeability.

191
00:10:15,815 --> 00:10:19,444
Just below felon
and just above shoplifter.

192
00:10:19,585 --> 00:10:21,348
[laughing]

193
00:10:21,487 --> 00:10:24,422
God, it's so sad. Women used to
make the pies and fake the orgasms.

194
00:10:24,557 --> 00:10:25,819
Now we fake the pies.

195
00:10:25,958 --> 00:10:27,926
That's a big improvement
as far as I'm concerned.

196
00:10:28,060 --> 00:10:30,995
Thank you. I was up all night.

197
00:10:31,130 --> 00:10:32,028
Oh, shit!

198
00:10:32,164 --> 00:10:33,256
There they are.

199
00:10:33,399 --> 00:10:34,832
[Kate] There they were.

200
00:10:34,967 --> 00:10:37,595
The most terrifying creatures
in captivity.

201
00:10:37,737 --> 00:10:39,534
The Momsters.

202
00:10:39,672 --> 00:10:41,697
On the right, Wendy Best,

203
00:10:41,841 --> 00:10:43,968
room parent,
field trip chaperone,

204
00:10:44,110 --> 00:10:46,101
parent association
vice president,

205
00:10:46,245 --> 00:10:50,272
also chief poobah in charge
of terrifying working mothers

206
00:10:50,416 --> 00:10:52,782
with her domestic prowess.

207
00:10:52,918 --> 00:10:55,512
And Janine LoPietro.

208
00:10:55,655 --> 00:10:58,021
She does Pilates, yoga,

209
00:10:58,157 --> 00:11:00,455
spinning and krav maga.

210
00:11:00,593 --> 00:11:03,528
Fitter than a Navy SEAL,
tougher, too.

211
00:11:03,663 --> 00:11:06,427
There you are, Kate.
I haven't seen you in ages.

212
00:11:06,565 --> 00:11:08,590
Honey, you look great.

213
00:11:08,734 --> 00:11:11,134
Well, I am just so jealous
of you girls.

214
00:11:11,270 --> 00:11:13,795
You get to wear high heels
and look nice all day.

215
00:11:13,939 --> 00:11:15,770
We just frump around at the park.

216
00:11:15,908 --> 00:11:17,637
Kate, I don't know how you do it.

217
00:11:17,777 --> 00:11:20,746
Wendy and l,
we always say that. Cookie?

218
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:24,509
- Oh... sure, thank you. Yummy.
- [laughs] Yeah.

219
00:11:24,650 --> 00:11:27,448
- Allison, please.
- No, thank you.

220
00:11:33,192 --> 00:11:34,386
- Bye.
- OK.

221
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:36,427
- Bye-bye.
- Bye!

222
00:11:36,562 --> 00:11:37,551
Bye.

223
00:11:41,434 --> 00:11:43,664
- Brush your hair.
- Did you see what she was wearing?

224
00:11:43,803 --> 00:11:47,534
You know, for me,
when I decided to have kids,

225
00:11:47,673 --> 00:11:49,971
I wanted to be the one
to raise them.

226
00:11:50,109 --> 00:11:53,601
But women make different choices
in their lives.

227
00:11:53,746 --> 00:11:57,842
And, uh, I don't judge.
I try not to... judge.

228
00:11:58,117 --> 00:12:01,177
- Bye. I'll talk to you later.
- Bye.

229
00:12:01,320 --> 00:12:03,117
- [barking]
- Oh, hello.

230
00:12:03,255 --> 00:12:04,745
- [barks]
- You should go home.

231
00:12:04,890 --> 00:12:07,654
Oh, oh! No,
don't go in the street!

232
00:12:07,793 --> 00:12:09,192
- Don't go in the street!
- [barks]

233
00:12:09,328 --> 00:12:10,795
[Kate] So now, of course,
I'm late.

234
00:12:10,930 --> 00:12:13,160
And I am gonna have to race
to the office

235
00:12:13,299 --> 00:12:14,926
to get there before my boss,
Clark.

236
00:12:15,067 --> 00:12:17,160
- Oh, hi, Clark.
- Oh, good morning.

237
00:12:17,303 --> 00:12:19,100
- How are you? Here, please.
- I'm well.

238
00:12:19,238 --> 00:12:21,763
- Allow me. Ladies first.
- Thank you.

239
00:12:21,907 --> 00:12:24,637
Say, are you running a little late this
morning? I've just come from a meeting.

240
00:12:24,777 --> 00:12:26,870
[bell dings]

241
00:12:27,847 --> 00:12:29,212
I have two choices here.

242
00:12:29,348 --> 00:12:32,181
The man's excuse:
bad traffic, downed power line,

243
00:12:32,318 --> 00:12:35,014
faulty carburetor. Or...

244
00:12:37,356 --> 00:12:39,483
- Mammogram.
- Oh.

245
00:12:39,625 --> 00:12:41,991
Well, then, I think I'll
just take the stairs.

246
00:12:42,128 --> 00:12:43,060
Good cardio.

247
00:12:43,195 --> 00:12:44,822
[elevator dings]

248
00:12:49,668 --> 00:12:51,431
Hey, morning, Jill.

249
00:13:03,115 --> 00:13:04,673
- Meeting.
- Yeah, just a second.

250
00:13:04,817 --> 00:13:06,444
Oh... Ugh! [laughs]

251
00:13:07,787 --> 00:13:09,846
Is that a Rice Krispie?

252
00:13:11,624 --> 00:13:13,489
- Oh.
- I hope.

253
00:13:15,060 --> 00:13:17,153
Oh, it's just dried
pancake batter.

254
00:13:17,296 --> 00:13:20,163
- Oh. Mm. Big relief.
- [bell dings]

255
00:13:20,299 --> 00:13:22,790
[Kate] Momo is a brilliant
junior research analyst.

256
00:13:22,935 --> 00:13:25,665
She has the work ethic
of a robot, and the warmth.

257
00:13:25,805 --> 00:13:29,104
But I don't care because
she devotes all that energy to her job.

258
00:13:29,241 --> 00:13:31,835
Kate Reddy? Well, she's
the best fund manager we have.

259
00:13:31,977 --> 00:13:35,469
She's great at her job,
works really, really hard.

260
00:13:35,614 --> 00:13:37,309
People think she's weird, though.

261
00:13:37,449 --> 00:13:40,350
She checks on her kids every day.

262
00:13:40,486 --> 00:13:42,954
[scoffs] Even during lunch,
when she should be working.

263
00:13:43,088 --> 00:13:45,716
OK, can we go
to the meeting now?

264
00:13:45,858 --> 00:13:48,588
Well, I guess. We don't have time
to do anything about your roots.

265
00:13:50,429 --> 00:13:52,761
So I heard Clark has gotten
some feedback from New York

266
00:13:52,898 --> 00:13:54,627
- on our fund proposal.
- Come on.

267
00:13:54,767 --> 00:13:56,962
New York never lets us run
with anything big.

268
00:13:57,102 --> 00:14:00,333
They treat the Boston office
like a sad stepchild.

269
00:14:00,472 --> 00:14:02,565
- Look, you're always tired...
- Morning.

270
00:14:02,708 --> 00:14:04,505
-...and insufficiently groomed.
- Welcome back.

271
00:14:04,643 --> 00:14:06,668
Once you smelled
like paste all day.

272
00:14:06,812 --> 00:14:08,871
But you write the best reports
on the floor.

273
00:14:09,014 --> 00:14:10,003
I doubt they even read them.

274
00:14:10,149 --> 00:14:11,741
And I certainly doubt
they picked one from here,

275
00:14:11,884 --> 00:14:14,352
but mark my words, if they did,
it will be Bunce's.

276
00:14:14,486 --> 00:14:18,547
Don't ask me how, but that
guy just keeps failing up.

277
00:14:19,525 --> 00:14:20,856
Oh, speak of the devil.

278
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:22,718
- Kate!
- [bell dings]

279
00:14:22,862 --> 00:14:25,194
[Kate] There's Chris Bunce.
He's our DOA:

280
00:14:25,331 --> 00:14:29,199
Designated Office Asshole.
Bunce loves that I have kids.

281
00:14:29,335 --> 00:14:31,963
Keeps me from getting an edge
on the competition,

282
00:14:32,104 --> 00:14:35,164
the one men get when they take clients
out for drinks and dinners

283
00:14:35,307 --> 00:14:37,832
and golf games. You know
what I'm talking about.

284
00:14:37,977 --> 00:14:39,103
The schmooze.

285
00:14:39,245 --> 00:14:41,406
There you are.
Everything OK this morning?

286
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:43,071
I was looking for you
and I couldn't find you.

287
00:14:43,215 --> 00:14:45,706
- Nothing with the kids, I hope.
- Oh, I had a...

288
00:14:45,851 --> 00:14:47,944
- Don't ask.
- [laughs] Anyway,

289
00:14:48,087 --> 00:14:51,022
I was just saying to Clark,
Kate is amazing, isn't she?

290
00:14:51,156 --> 00:14:52,623
I mean, I don't know
how she does it.

291
00:14:52,758 --> 00:14:54,248
- All those children...
- I have two.

292
00:14:54,393 --> 00:14:55,951
- It's so impressive.
- You have four.

293
00:14:56,095 --> 00:14:57,926
Yeah, but two of mine are twins.

294
00:15:01,533 --> 00:15:03,433
[groans] Bunce.

295
00:15:03,569 --> 00:15:06,697
How the hell is equality
between the sexes supposed to work?

296
00:15:06,839 --> 00:15:10,036
They can give you good jobs,
maternity leave,

297
00:15:10,175 --> 00:15:13,702
but until you program a man to notice
when you're out of toilet paper,

298
00:15:13,846 --> 00:15:15,939
the project is doomed.

299
00:15:16,081 --> 00:15:18,140
I resent when people say
there's a double standard.

300
00:15:18,284 --> 00:15:20,718
Men also have a lot to juggle.

301
00:15:20,853 --> 00:15:22,343
Take our shoes.

302
00:15:22,488 --> 00:15:25,616
Do women's shoes need to be
shiny all the time? No.

303
00:15:25,758 --> 00:15:28,022
You never see a woman
getting her shoes shined.

304
00:15:28,160 --> 00:15:30,128
Women's shoes
can be flat and dull.

305
00:15:30,262 --> 00:15:33,254
Not men's.
That's a double standard.

306
00:15:33,399 --> 00:15:35,264
Bunce had a great series
of meetings this week

307
00:15:35,401 --> 00:15:38,564
with the institutional investors from
Oakland about their retirement fund.

308
00:15:38,704 --> 00:15:42,504
Yes, meetings went great. Even got in
a little culture while they were here.

309
00:15:42,641 --> 00:15:44,836
- Took them to a dance show.
- [rock music plays]

310
00:15:44,977 --> 00:15:46,740
Hey! Whoo!

311
00:15:46,879 --> 00:15:49,575
Interpretive.
Interpretive dance show.

312
00:15:49,715 --> 00:15:52,149
Nice work, Bunce.
Moving on to new business.

313
00:15:52,284 --> 00:15:55,447
Jack Abelhammer in our New York office
has sparked to a proposal

314
00:15:55,587 --> 00:15:57,680
from this office, and he'd
like to meet the author.

315
00:15:57,823 --> 00:16:01,520
Kick the tires, see if it's an
idea worth bringing to Harcourt.

316
00:16:01,660 --> 00:16:05,960
Bunce, I know how long
you've waited for this chance.

317
00:16:09,335 --> 00:16:11,860
Keep waiting.
Congratulations, Kate.

318
00:16:12,004 --> 00:16:14,939
You'll be heading to New York tonight.
You've got a 9am with Abelhammer.

319
00:16:16,008 --> 00:16:17,373
Really?

320
00:16:17,509 --> 00:16:19,943
Guess someone finally
read one of your proposals.

321
00:16:20,079 --> 00:16:21,706
[Kate] Wow!

322
00:16:21,847 --> 00:16:24,372
[Bunce] Congrats to the B team.

323
00:16:24,516 --> 00:16:26,074
OK.

324
00:16:29,688 --> 00:16:32,248
If this works out,
this could be a big step up.

325
00:16:32,391 --> 00:16:34,985
A lot of travel,
a lot of one-on-one with Abelhammer.

326
00:16:35,127 --> 00:16:37,755
It's gonna be great.
Plus, gives your kids a chance

327
00:16:37,896 --> 00:16:39,989
to spend all that extra quality time
they've been hoping for...

328
00:16:40,132 --> 00:16:43,033
...with your nanny.
And your husband will be thrilled.

329
00:16:43,168 --> 00:16:44,635
Congratulations.

330
00:16:48,140 --> 00:16:49,767
[Momo] You know she's married,
right?

331
00:16:49,908 --> 00:16:52,468
Well, in her marriage,
she has to call her husband

332
00:16:52,611 --> 00:16:56,047
every time she has to work late
or go across the country

333
00:16:56,181 --> 00:16:57,910
or she can't pick up her kids
from school.

334
00:16:58,050 --> 00:16:59,244
It's like she's on parole.

335
00:16:59,385 --> 00:17:01,319
And that is why I'm not
getting married

336
00:17:01,453 --> 00:17:02,647
or having children.

337
00:17:02,788 --> 00:17:04,380
I did have a fish once.

338
00:17:04,523 --> 00:17:06,491
But then he kept looking at me
with these eyes,

339
00:17:06,625 --> 00:17:08,252
Iike, "Feed me."

340
00:17:08,394 --> 00:17:10,294
So I flushed him.

341
00:17:10,429 --> 00:17:12,556
His name was Derek.

342
00:17:12,698 --> 00:17:14,063
Derek Chan.

343
00:17:16,335 --> 00:17:17,768
[computer beeps]

344
00:17:17,903 --> 00:17:20,098
[Allison] Hey, let's blow
off work early, go to a bar,

345
00:17:20,239 --> 00:17:22,707
pretend we're single.
And rested.

346
00:17:22,841 --> 00:17:25,366
Either one. Maybe both.

347
00:17:25,511 --> 00:17:26,773
[computer dings]

348
00:17:26,912 --> 00:17:28,641
[man] Just confirming
our meeting tomorrow.

349
00:17:28,781 --> 00:17:31,341
9am. Looking forward
to meeting you.

350
00:17:31,483 --> 00:17:32,950
Jack Abelhammer.

351
00:17:36,321 --> 00:17:38,721
[Kate] Would love to get
blotto, sadly can't.

352
00:17:38,857 --> 00:17:42,054
Have to go to New York
and blow somebody.

353
00:17:43,462 --> 00:17:44,986
[computer beeps]

354
00:17:46,765 --> 00:17:49,598
Dear Jack, looking forward
to meeting you, too.

355
00:17:49,735 --> 00:17:52,169
Kate Reddy.

356
00:17:52,304 --> 00:17:53,430
[computer beeps]

357
00:17:57,209 --> 00:18:00,201
[Kate] Richard, this thing
is a long shot, I promise you.

358
00:18:00,345 --> 00:18:04,805
I have to pitch to him, and he'd
have to pick me over everyone else.

359
00:18:04,950 --> 00:18:08,909
And... the chances of those two things
happening are very slim.

360
00:18:09,054 --> 00:18:11,784
Oh, well, if it comes down
to your ability to pitch

361
00:18:11,924 --> 00:18:15,052
and the quality of your idea,
honey, of course you're getting this.

362
00:18:15,194 --> 00:18:17,355
Good luck at your meeting, honey.
And please don't worry about me.

363
00:18:17,496 --> 00:18:22,456
It's such a short trip. No one will even
notice I'm gone again. I promise.

364
00:18:22,601 --> 00:18:24,933
No! You just got back.

365
00:18:25,070 --> 00:18:27,561
Honey, I know,
but it's just... It's one night.

366
00:18:27,706 --> 00:18:30,004
And I will have this with me.
You call me any time.

367
00:18:30,142 --> 00:18:31,131
Whatever, Mom.

368
00:18:32,544 --> 00:18:34,637
[Ben babbling]

369
00:18:38,884 --> 00:18:40,943
At least you don't hate me.

370
00:18:41,086 --> 00:18:42,280
[cooing]

371
00:18:51,330 --> 00:18:53,696
Um... did...

372
00:18:53,832 --> 00:18:55,390
Did you take Ben
to get a hair cut?

373
00:18:55,534 --> 00:18:56,660
Yeah, his bangs
were in his eyes,

374
00:18:56,802 --> 00:18:58,269
so I took him to that
place on the corner.

375
00:18:59,271 --> 00:19:00,329
Oh.

376
00:19:01,440 --> 00:19:03,635
Oh... he looks...

377
00:19:04,576 --> 00:19:07,204
I mean, it's adorable.
Thank you. I just...

378
00:19:07,346 --> 00:19:09,211
It was...
That was his first hair cut.

379
00:19:09,348 --> 00:19:11,509
- So...
- Yeah, I wanted to call.

380
00:19:11,650 --> 00:19:13,675
I just didn't want to disturb you at
work. I didn't wanna bother you.

381
00:19:13,819 --> 00:19:18,017
Oh, no! Paula, no, it's...
No, you're never bothering me.

382
00:19:18,157 --> 00:19:21,615
Nothing is more important to me than the
kids. I'm always happy to hear about

383
00:19:21,760 --> 00:19:25,821
- any little or big thing. Honestly.
- Got it.

384
00:19:25,964 --> 00:19:27,727
Great, thanks.

385
00:19:29,701 --> 00:19:31,396
- I love you.
- Bye-bye, Mama.

386
00:19:31,537 --> 00:19:33,562
Bye-bye, bunny.

387
00:19:33,705 --> 00:19:35,297
- I love you. Paula, you'll call me?
- Yes.

388
00:19:35,440 --> 00:19:37,203
For anything?
I don't care the reason.

389
00:19:37,342 --> 00:19:39,833
- Bye.
- Come on.

390
00:19:39,978 --> 00:19:42,879
Bye. Bye-bye.

391
00:19:43,649 --> 00:19:45,048
Bye-bye!

392
00:19:50,856 --> 00:19:52,551
- [sobbing]
- [Kate] The books say

393
00:19:52,691 --> 00:19:55,990
children get over separation
anxiety by two years.

394
00:19:56,128 --> 00:19:57,925
- [woman speaking indistinctly]
- Good evening.

395
00:19:58,063 --> 00:20:00,395
- [woman] That was weird. [laughs]
- [sobbing]

396
00:20:00,532 --> 00:20:02,557
[Kate] No age limit
is given for mothers.

397
00:20:02,701 --> 00:20:06,262
He'll never have his
first hair cut again. Never.

398
00:20:06,538 --> 00:20:09,564
[pop music plays]

399
00:20:14,279 --> 00:20:16,941
They didn't have purple tights
in your size, Em,

400
00:20:17,082 --> 00:20:20,074
but I'll keep looking.
I promise. OK?

401
00:20:20,219 --> 00:20:21,880
OK, honey.

402
00:20:22,020 --> 00:20:24,853
- [horn honking]
- Do you want a brush?

403
00:20:24,990 --> 00:20:26,480
What, I'm a little itchy.
Is that a crime?

404
00:20:26,625 --> 00:20:28,058
- [ring tone sounds]
- Oh. Hello?

405
00:20:28,193 --> 00:20:29,626
Today's playdate's
in the park, right?

406
00:20:29,761 --> 00:20:31,695
You just have to confirm
that with Owen's nanny?

407
00:20:31,830 --> 00:20:33,821
Yeah, I have the number.
Can you hold on?

408
00:20:33,966 --> 00:20:35,797
Just hold on, OK?

409
00:20:35,934 --> 00:20:37,663
No, I think I have the number.
Can you hold on a second?

410
00:20:37,803 --> 00:20:39,566
I think I have the number.

411
00:20:39,705 --> 00:20:42,936
OK. Hold on.
Can you hold that for a second?

412
00:20:44,042 --> 00:20:45,669
Can you...?

413
00:20:45,811 --> 00:20:47,369
Sorry.

414
00:20:47,512 --> 00:20:49,139
Do you mind?

415
00:20:49,281 --> 00:20:51,806
[toy] Hello, baby. Bye-bye.

416
00:20:51,950 --> 00:20:54,817
- [Momo] Why is this wet?
- That doesn't belong there.

417
00:20:55,954 --> 00:20:58,548
Sorry, it's kind of precious.

418
00:20:58,690 --> 00:21:00,089
[Momo] Something
smells like raw meat.

419
00:21:00,225 --> 00:21:01,590
I wondered where that was.

420
00:21:03,428 --> 00:21:05,453
A-ha! Yeah! Yep.

421
00:21:05,597 --> 00:21:07,929
Yep, yep, yep. Got it, got it.
Got the number.

422
00:21:08,066 --> 00:21:09,727
Wait, are you...
are you still there?

423
00:21:10,769 --> 00:21:11,861
Go ahead, say it.

424
00:21:12,004 --> 00:21:15,440
- Say what?
- Oh, just get it out.

425
00:21:15,574 --> 00:21:16,973
No, it's just...

426
00:21:18,744 --> 00:21:19,733
I don't know how you do it.

427
00:21:19,878 --> 00:21:21,345
Well, you will, one day.

428
00:21:21,480 --> 00:21:24,142
[laughs] No, no, no.
I am not having kids.

429
00:21:24,283 --> 00:21:25,944
Really? Why not?

430
00:21:26,084 --> 00:21:28,416
- Well, for one thing...
- Can you just hold this for a second?

431
00:21:28,553 --> 00:21:32,011
Momo, I promise you
that being a mother

432
00:21:32,157 --> 00:21:33,852
is one of the most rewarding

433
00:21:33,992 --> 00:21:36,961
and enriching experiences
a person can have.

434
00:21:37,095 --> 00:21:39,791
It's probably just my stress
eczema flaring up again.

435
00:21:41,099 --> 00:21:43,829
- I'm sorry.
- [elevator dings]

436
00:21:44,903 --> 00:21:47,201
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

437
00:21:47,339 --> 00:21:48,601
- He'll be right with you.
- Great, thanks.

438
00:21:48,740 --> 00:21:52,141
- [cell phone rings]
- Oh, sorry. My kids love that music.

439
00:21:52,277 --> 00:21:54,711
Hey, Allison, I'm just
stepping into a meeting.

440
00:21:54,846 --> 00:21:57,178
- Can I call you back maybe?
- [Allison] Sure.

441
00:21:57,316 --> 00:21:58,510
But why did you send me an email

442
00:21:58,650 --> 00:22:00,242
saying that you were
looking forward to meeting me?

443
00:22:00,385 --> 00:22:02,512
- What?
- Last night, when I asked you

444
00:22:02,654 --> 00:22:04,747
if you wanted to get a drink,
I just reread your response

445
00:22:04,890 --> 00:22:07,859
- and it doesn't make any sense. So...
- No.

446
00:22:07,993 --> 00:22:12,157
No, no, no. I didn't send you that
email. I sent you a different one...

447
00:22:13,265 --> 00:22:14,857
Oh, my God! Wait!

448
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:18,993
I... I didn't send you
an email about a b job?

449
00:22:19,137 --> 00:22:22,265
Uh, no, honey.
I mean, not yesterday.

450
00:22:22,407 --> 00:22:23,704
- Oh, my God!
- Kate Reddy?

451
00:22:26,278 --> 00:22:27,939
Jack Abelhammer.

452
00:22:28,080 --> 00:22:30,844
Momo Hahn.
It is an honor to meet you, sir.

453
00:22:32,217 --> 00:22:34,651
- Shall we?
- Uh... yeah... Listen,

454
00:22:34,786 --> 00:22:39,189
Jack, um... Jack, about the email
that I sent yesterday,

455
00:22:39,324 --> 00:22:42,623
the, um... the, uh...
activity mentioned,

456
00:22:42,761 --> 00:22:45,286
- that's not... I don't...
- Oh, yes, I saw that.

457
00:22:45,430 --> 00:22:48,866
Are you still planning to start
the meeting with that action item?

458
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:51,992
Uh, sorry. There's...
There's been some, uh...

459
00:22:52,137 --> 00:22:54,867
Some budget cutbacks lately.
So no.

460
00:22:55,006 --> 00:22:56,200
[chuckles] Oh, disappointing.

461
00:22:56,341 --> 00:22:57,399
- [cell phone rings]
- Oh, sorry.

462
00:22:57,542 --> 00:22:59,908
I'm gonna silence this thing.
Yeah, here I am...

463
00:23:00,045 --> 00:23:01,672
- I'm silencing it.
- [phone beeps]

464
00:23:01,813 --> 00:23:04,941
[laughs] Sorry, again. Sorry.

465
00:23:11,590 --> 00:23:12,579
Everything OK?

466
00:23:14,960 --> 00:23:17,622
Yep! [laughs]

467
00:23:19,431 --> 00:23:20,398
Oh, my God!

468
00:23:20,532 --> 00:23:22,363
We received a lot of proposals,

469
00:23:22,501 --> 00:23:25,061
but I was most intrigued
by your notion of an

470
00:23:25,203 --> 00:23:28,502
individual investor
retirement fund.

471
00:23:28,640 --> 00:23:30,665
In order to make that work,

472
00:23:30,809 --> 00:23:34,142
you'd have to pick stocks
with a big dividend yield.

473
00:23:34,279 --> 00:23:36,941
Well, of course, but you know
you also have to avoid the value traps.

474
00:23:37,082 --> 00:23:39,209
I think you'll see that I've
targeted a few industries

