1186
00:58:32,342 --> 00:58:35,903
- Those look great.
- Thank you. [chuckles]

1187
00:58:37,614 --> 00:58:39,479
Thanks for doing this.

1188
00:58:39,616 --> 00:58:41,516
Those smell delicious, Kate.

1189
00:58:45,655 --> 00:58:48,988
- So a bunch of snowmen are standing...
- Oh, no!

1190
00:58:49,125 --> 00:58:51,650
A bunch of snowmen are standing
in front of the barbershop,

1191
00:58:51,794 --> 00:58:53,557
- and one of them says...
- Who smells carrots.

1192
00:58:53,696 --> 00:58:56,859
- Uh... Oh, come on!
- Same one as last year.

1193
00:58:57,000 --> 00:58:59,093
- Thank you.
- You ruined my joke!

1194
00:58:59,235 --> 00:59:02,227
- You ruined my joke!
-...30 years ago...

1195
00:59:02,372 --> 00:59:03,737
- [laughing]
- That's my joke!

1196
00:59:03,873 --> 00:59:06,569
- I don't get it.
- Because of their nose.

1197
00:59:06,709 --> 00:59:09,974
- 'Cause their nose is a carrot.
- You know the pond is frozen.

1198
00:59:10,113 --> 00:59:12,274
So if anybody wants
to go skating tomorrow...

1199
00:59:12,415 --> 00:59:14,610
Well, I promised Em that we were gonna
build a snowman tomorrow, right?

1200
00:59:14,751 --> 00:59:16,946
- Yeah.
- We can do it at the pond.

1201
00:59:17,086 --> 00:59:20,852
[Richard] Oh, that was great,
Mom. What did you do this year?

1202
00:59:20,990 --> 00:59:23,254
[mother] I ran out of canned
pumpkin, so I had to...

1203
00:59:23,393 --> 00:59:25,054
- [phone rings]
- [Richard] You used cream?

1204
00:59:25,194 --> 00:59:26,752
[mother] Yeah.
I used light cream,

1205
00:59:26,896 --> 00:59:29,296
- but heavy cream's better.
- You OK?

1206
00:59:29,432 --> 00:59:31,024
- Yeah, she's here.
- Yeah.

1207
00:59:31,167 --> 00:59:33,226
Kate, it's for you.
It's someone named Nono.

1208
00:59:33,369 --> 00:59:35,735
Oh, no, Momo.
I'm gonna take it in the other room.

1209
00:59:35,872 --> 00:59:38,204
[father] Momo,
what does that mean?

1210
00:59:38,341 --> 00:59:41,276
[indistinct chatter]

1211
00:59:41,411 --> 00:59:43,242
- Are you OK?
- [Momo] What is the matter with you?

1212
00:59:43,379 --> 00:59:44,778
- I left you 100 messages.
- OK.

1213
00:59:44,914 --> 00:59:46,939
- Jack is trying to reach you.
- OK, I'll check my phone.

1214
00:59:47,083 --> 00:59:48,744
[mother] Remember Barry Brentwood?

1215
00:59:48,885 --> 00:59:50,409
- He was arrested.
- Mm.

1216
00:59:50,553 --> 00:59:51,781
- [father] What?
- [mother] He's going to prison.

1217
00:59:51,921 --> 00:59:53,388
- Really?
- Barry Brentwood?

1218
00:59:53,523 --> 00:59:55,218
- [mother] Barry Brentwood.
- [Richard] What did he do?

1219
00:59:55,358 --> 00:59:57,588
[mother] Oh, my God.
He got into something

1220
00:59:57,727 --> 01:00:00,423
with a drug dealer, and they
hired him to kill somebody...

1221
01:00:01,331 --> 01:00:03,162
[father] Oh, no.

1222
01:00:04,767 --> 01:00:05,756
Who did he kill?

1223
01:00:05,902 --> 01:00:07,426
[mother] I don't know!
I don't know. Somebody...

1224
01:00:07,570 --> 01:00:11,267
Hi, Jack, sorry I missed your
calls. My cell reception is...

1225
01:00:11,407 --> 01:00:13,898
Um, anyway, what's up?

1226
01:00:14,043 --> 01:00:16,238
[Jack] Sorry, Kate.
Harcourt's schedule changed.

1227
01:00:16,379 --> 01:00:19,041
- He can only hear the pitch tomorrow.
- Oh, shit.

1228
01:00:19,182 --> 01:00:20,740
Well, um, when did that happen?

1229
01:00:20,883 --> 01:00:24,114
[Jack] If you can't make it,
maybe Bunce can take over.

1230
01:00:24,253 --> 01:00:28,485
So Harcourt has to go to Hong Kong
the day after tomorrow for a week.

1231
01:00:28,625 --> 01:00:31,753
There's some emergency
with the Asian brokerage house.

1232
01:00:31,894 --> 01:00:35,853
Which means that tomorrow
morning is our only shot

1233
01:00:35,999 --> 01:00:37,489
to get this thing in front of him.

1234
01:00:37,634 --> 01:00:39,499
But Jack said Bunce would do it.

1235
01:00:39,636 --> 01:00:42,002
- Let him go.
- Come on, Richard.

1236
01:00:42,138 --> 01:00:45,665
I can't let Bunce take this. You know
how hard I've been working on it.

1237
01:00:45,808 --> 01:00:49,801
But I can't control
how and where we pitch it.

1238
01:00:49,946 --> 01:00:53,882
It's not my fault. I have... I have
planned everything so this exact thing

1239
01:00:54,017 --> 01:00:55,951
would not happen.

1240
01:00:57,420 --> 01:00:59,945
But we were supposed
to make a snowman.

1241
01:01:00,089 --> 01:01:03,388
Sweetie, I know. Listen.

1242
01:01:03,526 --> 01:01:06,154
The very next time there's snow,

1243
01:01:06,295 --> 01:01:09,492
we're gonna make a snowman.
I promise. OK?

1244
01:01:09,632 --> 01:01:11,623
You already promised.

1245
01:01:11,768 --> 01:01:15,898
[Ben babbling]

1246
01:01:16,039 --> 01:01:18,872
Hey. Bye-bye, bunny.

1247
01:01:19,008 --> 01:01:22,171
- Bye-bye, Mama.
- [gasps] Oh, my God!

1248
01:01:22,311 --> 01:01:26,805
- [Ben laughs]
- You spoke!

1249
01:01:26,949 --> 01:01:28,917
Ben!

1250
01:01:29,052 --> 01:01:31,247
You said, "Bye-bye, Mama."

1251
01:01:31,387 --> 01:01:33,378
- He spoke!
- "Bye-bye, Mama."

1252
01:01:33,523 --> 01:01:35,423
Well, it'll come in handy.

1253
01:01:37,694 --> 01:01:39,924
- Richard, I'm...
- You gotta go, Kate.

1254
01:01:41,230 --> 01:01:43,630
And we'll talk about it
when you get back, OK?

1255
01:01:45,802 --> 01:01:47,963
[car starts]

1256
01:01:51,607 --> 01:01:52,835
Bye.

1257
01:02:00,817 --> 01:02:05,254
Oh, we all heard
about Thanksgiving.

1258
01:02:05,388 --> 01:02:08,880
Leaving right after dinner?
Seriously? Who does that?

1259
01:02:09,025 --> 01:02:10,959
No, I prefer
to be with my family.

1260
01:02:11,094 --> 01:02:14,621
You know, clean up while my husband
and his friends watch football

1261
01:02:14,764 --> 01:02:18,598
and I chase after the kids because
they've had eight slices of pecan pie.

1262
01:02:18,735 --> 01:02:22,637
Then I make 11 sandwiches of leftovers
for everybody for the next day.

1263
01:02:22,772 --> 01:02:26,230
Listen to my mother-in-law yammer on
for the 15th time

1264
01:02:26,375 --> 01:02:28,172
that my stuffing was too dry.

1265
01:02:28,311 --> 01:02:30,245
Like I've never
heard that one before.

1266
01:02:30,379 --> 01:02:32,813
[sighs]

1267
01:02:32,949 --> 01:02:34,416
I just...

1268
01:02:36,319 --> 01:02:39,846
It's family, and I love it.
I love it.

1269
01:02:41,023 --> 01:02:42,251
[Momo] I'm feeling
much better, thanks.

1270
01:02:42,391 --> 01:02:43,915
- Let's focus on the proposal.
- [Kate] OK.

1271
01:02:44,060 --> 01:02:46,028
I was thinking we could
start with an overview

1272
01:02:46,162 --> 01:02:49,097
of dividend payers
versus non-payers.

1273
01:02:49,232 --> 01:02:50,790
[groaning]

1274
01:02:50,933 --> 01:02:53,424
- [moaning]
- Whoa! Careful!

1275
01:02:53,569 --> 01:02:56,561
Or you could... throw up
again a few more times.

1276
01:02:56,706 --> 01:02:59,140
[toilet flushes]

1277
01:03:00,209 --> 01:03:02,507
- Momo, you OK?
- [Momo] Yeah, I'm fine.

1278
01:03:02,645 --> 01:03:04,909
[moans] This does not
feel like a miracle.

1279
01:03:05,047 --> 01:03:09,006
Oh! Don't worry, morning sickness
only lasts about, um,

1280
01:03:09,152 --> 01:03:10,084
nine months.

1281
01:03:10,920 --> 01:03:11,944
[groans]

1282
01:03:12,088 --> 01:03:15,319
Ooh, oh, yeah.
I've been there.

1283
01:03:18,694 --> 01:03:22,323
- You OK?
- Don't I look OK? Let's walk.

1284
01:03:22,465 --> 01:03:25,628
Oh, Momo! Momo, Momo! Momo!

1285
01:03:27,737 --> 01:03:30,171
Oh, my God!

1286
01:03:30,306 --> 01:03:33,002
It's official.
I'm disgusting.

1287
01:03:34,076 --> 01:03:36,442
How did this happen?
Don't answer that.

1288
01:03:37,980 --> 01:03:39,470
[Momo] I didn't get any
sleep last night.

1289
01:03:39,615 --> 01:03:41,242
I think this baby's
on a treadmill.

1290
01:03:41,384 --> 01:03:43,511
- [phone rings]
- [Kate] Thank you.

1291
01:03:44,420 --> 01:03:46,888
- Hey. Hey, good morning.
- Good morning.

1292
01:03:47,023 --> 01:03:49,787
Thank you for your lovely note
and the room is beautiful.

1293
01:03:49,926 --> 01:03:53,521
You know what? You knocked yourself out
getting this thing right.

1294
01:03:53,663 --> 01:03:54,755
You deserve a nice room

1295
01:03:54,897 --> 01:03:57,525
and if this thing has any chance at all
with Harcourt, it's gonna be because

1296
01:03:57,667 --> 01:04:00,795
- of the way you pitch it.
- He's ready for you.

1297
01:04:00,937 --> 01:04:02,097
Let's go. [clears throat]

1298
01:04:02,238 --> 01:04:04,399
Remember, we're a great team, Bill.

1299
01:04:04,540 --> 01:04:06,064
[chuckles]

1300
01:04:08,477 --> 01:04:09,409
Good morning.

1301
01:04:09,545 --> 01:04:10,978
We're here today

1302
01:04:11,113 --> 01:04:13,411
to talk about possibility.

1303
01:04:13,549 --> 01:04:16,677
The possibility of a
new financial product

1304
01:04:16,819 --> 01:04:20,084
that could restore some of the faith
we've lost with our customer.

1305
01:04:20,223 --> 01:04:24,182
We wanna show them that we understand,
that we wanna make money

1306
01:04:24,327 --> 01:04:26,022
for them as well as for us.

1307
01:04:26,162 --> 01:04:29,188
So I would like to start off
with a few charts

1308
01:04:29,332 --> 01:04:32,824
showing you the dividend
base strategy we've devised.

1309
01:04:38,474 --> 01:04:40,339
- Momo!
- [snorts]

1310
01:04:40,476 --> 01:04:42,376
[computer dings]

1311
01:04:42,511 --> 01:04:45,309
- Which will show you...
- [Kate] The PowerPoint presentation

1312
01:04:45,448 --> 01:04:47,109
was going really well.

1313
01:04:47,250 --> 01:04:51,277
No one could tell Momo and I
had been up all night rehearsing.

1314
01:04:51,420 --> 01:04:53,217
Until...

1315
01:04:56,826 --> 01:05:00,660
OK, 300 presentations last year,
and I never messed up once.

1316
01:05:00,796 --> 01:05:03,230
It's not my fault. The pregnancy
did something to my brain.

1317
01:05:03,366 --> 01:05:06,096
I don't get it, OK? The baby
is nowhere near your brain.

1318
01:05:06,235 --> 01:05:07,930
What else can it do to your brain?

1319
01:05:10,706 --> 01:05:12,003
Mm!

1320
01:05:15,378 --> 01:05:17,107
I'm sorry.
I'm so sorry. I was so nervous.

1321
01:05:17,246 --> 01:05:19,544
- I forgot the whole...
- Are you kidding? That was a home run.

1322
01:05:19,682 --> 01:05:22,173
I didn't have to say a word.
He loved it. I could tell.

1323
01:05:22,318 --> 01:05:24,616
- Really?
- Really! You lunatic!

1324
01:05:24,754 --> 01:05:26,949
God, I love...

1325
01:05:27,089 --> 01:05:28,784
I love the way you ran that.
It was brilliant.

1326
01:05:28,925 --> 01:05:30,358
- Absolutely brilliant. There he is.
- Thank you.

1327
01:05:30,493 --> 01:05:32,757
- Let me close this.
- OK, OK.

1328
01:05:32,895 --> 01:05:34,157
OK.

1329
01:05:35,464 --> 01:05:36,954
You OK?

1330
01:05:43,572 --> 01:05:45,563
[Momo] Kate, I hope
I didn't blow this for us.

1331
01:05:45,708 --> 01:05:47,573
[Kate] No, it's fine.
Don't worry about it.

1332
01:05:58,087 --> 01:06:00,647
[sighs] Just like I thought.
He thinks you're terrific.

1333
01:06:00,790 --> 01:06:02,951
Wants to know what we've been
doing hiding you in Boston.

1334
01:06:03,092 --> 01:06:04,650
- Really?
- Yep. He's going to take me to lunch.

1335
01:06:04,794 --> 01:06:07,194
He's got a lot of questions.
But they sound like the right questions.

1336
01:06:07,330 --> 01:06:09,594
The ones that mean he's serious.

1337
01:06:10,433 --> 01:06:12,196
So should l...?

1338
01:06:12,335 --> 01:06:14,667
Should I go back? To Boston?

1339
01:06:14,804 --> 01:06:17,398
Yeah, I guess. Uh, I'll
call you if I hear anything.

1340
01:06:17,540 --> 01:06:18,564
- OK?
- OK.

1341
01:06:19,775 --> 01:06:21,640
You know the first thing he said to me?

1342
01:06:21,777 --> 01:06:24,678
- Where did I get this idea?
- Oh...

1343
01:06:29,685 --> 01:06:31,880
I hope he told him he
got the idea from you.

1344
01:06:32,021 --> 01:06:35,013
Well, I mean, you know, we really, he
and I really developed it together.

1345
01:06:35,157 --> 01:06:38,593
It's changed a lot
since the version that I started with.

1346
01:06:38,728 --> 01:06:41,526
It's not right.
You should be at the lunch.

1347
01:06:41,664 --> 01:06:43,791
- Harcourt should know you.
- He will. He will.

1348
01:06:43,933 --> 01:06:47,994
I mean, he does. I'm the one that really
pitched it in the meeting, not Jack.

1349
01:06:48,137 --> 01:06:50,799
Yeah. But now Jack is going
to lunch with Harcourt,

1350
01:06:50,940 --> 01:06:54,467
and you can just bet by dessert,
this whole thing will be Jack's idea.

1351
01:06:54,610 --> 01:06:57,738
These guys don't get to the top
by giving credit to the junior team.

1352
01:07:00,750 --> 01:07:02,012
What am I doing?

1353
01:07:03,252 --> 01:07:04,310
You gotta come with me.

1354
01:07:05,321 --> 01:07:07,221
You're where I got this idea.

1355
01:07:07,356 --> 01:07:08,323
It's yours.

1356
01:07:08,457 --> 01:07:10,049
We're a team.

1357
01:07:10,192 --> 01:07:11,955
And teams stick together.

1358
01:07:13,329 --> 01:07:14,728
Right, Momo?

1359
01:07:15,765 --> 01:07:17,562
[Kate] So it's the 18th frame,

1360
01:07:17,700 --> 01:07:20,601
or maybe the 28th frame,
I can't remember.

1361
01:07:20,736 --> 01:07:21,998
- [Jack] Eighteenth.
- [Kate] Eighteenth frame.

1362
01:07:22,138 --> 01:07:25,039
And, um, you know,
a lot of tension in the bowling alley.

1363
01:07:25,174 --> 01:07:28,200
In fact, I think everybody
was completely silent.

1364
01:07:28,344 --> 01:07:29,777
- And this gentleman...
- Except you.

1365
01:07:29,912 --> 01:07:33,370
- [laughs]
- This elegant,

1366
01:07:33,516 --> 01:07:37,213
wherever you're from,
gets up... [laughs]

1367
01:07:37,353 --> 01:07:41,119
Gets up and he says,
"Max's Automotive is going down!"

1368
01:07:41,257 --> 01:07:42,747
- Just like that.
- Just like that!

1369
01:07:42,892 --> 01:07:45,656
- I came out of my shell.
- [laughs]

1370
01:07:45,795 --> 01:07:48,787
I think with
a Bronx accent, right?

1371
01:07:48,931 --> 01:07:51,593
- He fit right in.
- [laughs]

1372
01:07:51,734 --> 01:07:53,099
[Harcourt] It was a pleasure
to meet you.

1373
01:07:53,235 --> 01:07:54,566
- [Kate] Likewise.
- [Harcourt] Jack will tell you

1374
01:07:54,703 --> 01:07:57,001
that I like to say no,
and I had my doubts coming in,

1375
01:07:57,139 --> 01:07:59,130
but you made a very compelling case.

1376
01:07:59,275 --> 01:08:02,039
- I am intrigued.
- Oh, my God. Well, thank you.

1377
01:08:02,178 --> 01:08:04,146
Thank you, thank you.

1378
01:08:04,280 --> 01:08:06,646
You're right,
she does like to say thank you.

1379
01:08:06,782 --> 01:08:08,477
I'll be in touch.

1380
01:08:13,322 --> 01:08:17,122
[laughing] That was miraculous.

1381
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:18,988
He never says anything positive.

1382
01:08:19,128 --> 01:08:20,527
My God, you think he'll go for it?

1383
01:08:20,663 --> 01:08:22,858
Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah.
I think we got a good shot at this.

1384
01:08:22,998 --> 01:08:24,397
- Absolutely.
- Oh, my God!

1385
01:08:24,533 --> 01:08:26,398
I can't believe it went so well!

1386
01:08:26,535 --> 01:08:28,696
- Think you're gonna make your plane?
- Uh, I don't know.

1387
01:08:28,838 --> 01:08:31,363
- I have to see what time it is.
- OK.

1388
01:08:31,507 --> 01:08:33,975
Wow, will you look at that?
This thing finally quit.

1389
01:08:34,110 --> 01:08:36,271
- Battery died?
- Yeah, I didn't charge it.

1390
01:08:36,412 --> 01:08:38,312
OK, OK, hold on.
Use mine.

1391
01:08:38,447 --> 01:08:40,506
That's odd, look at this.

1392
01:08:40,649 --> 01:08:42,082
I got a bunch of missed calls.

1393
01:08:42,952 --> 01:08:44,442
All from you.

1394
01:08:46,055 --> 01:08:47,682
[Kate] Richard, honey, I'm on my way.

1395
01:08:47,823 --> 01:08:50,223
I'll be there as soon as I can.

1396
01:08:55,564 --> 01:08:56,997
[woman] But keep a close eye on him.

1397
01:08:57,133 --> 01:09:00,432
If he experiences any dizziness
or nausea tonight,

1398
01:09:00,569 --> 01:09:02,901
- call us immediately.
- Thank you so much.

1399
01:09:03,038 --> 01:09:06,166
- Emily?
- Hi, bunny.

1400
01:09:06,308 --> 01:09:08,469
- Hi, sweetie.
- Mommy.

1401
01:09:08,611 --> 01:09:10,977
Oh, hi, baby.
What happened?

1402
01:09:11,113 --> 01:09:16,483
Well, he tripped on that place in the
carpet and fell down the stairs.

1403
01:09:16,619 --> 01:09:18,450
Oh! Sweetie...

1404
01:09:19,989 --> 01:09:21,786
[alarm chirps]

1405
01:09:29,565 --> 01:09:32,625
[Allison] A man announces he's going to
leave the office to be with a child,

1406
01:09:32,768 --> 01:09:38,138
and he is hailed as a selfless,
doting, paternal role model.

1407
01:09:38,274 --> 01:09:41,266
A woman announces that she's going to
leave the office to be with a child

1408
01:09:41,410 --> 01:09:44,277
on its sick bed, and she is damned

1409
01:09:44,413 --> 01:09:46,540
as disorganized, irresponsible,

1410
01:09:46,682 --> 01:09:49,549
and showing insufficient commitment.

1411
01:09:49,685 --> 01:09:52,518
[cloth tearing]

1412
01:09:55,257 --> 01:09:58,124
[tearing]

1413
01:10:02,298 --> 01:10:03,788
I know, it was
on the list, right?

1414
01:10:03,933 --> 01:10:06,026
No. No, forget the list,
Richard. You live here.

1415
01:10:06,168 --> 01:10:07,931
Haven't you tripped on that
thing a million times?

1416
